        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1977-03-31T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1977-03-31T00:00:00-05:00" n="10"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d10">
                <head>10. Memorandum From the President’s Assistant for National Security Affairs
                    (Brzezinski) to Secretary of Defense Brown<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d10fn1">Source: Carter Library, National Security Affairs,
                        Brzezinski Material, Subject File, Box 47, Nuclear War Doctrine: Limited
                        Nuclear Options (<gloss target="#t_LNO_1">LNO</gloss>) and Regional Nuclear
                        Options (<gloss target="#t_RNO_1">RNO</gloss>): 3/77–1/80. Top Secret;
                        Sensitive. Carter initialed the top of the memorandum and wrote “ok.”</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1977-03-31">March 31, 1977</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The President has directed me to ask you and, to the extent appropriate, the
                    Chairman of the <gloss target="#t_JCS_1">JCS</gloss>, to provide: <pb
                        facs="0060" n="35" xml:id="pg_35"/>
                    <list>
                        <label>(a)</label>
                        <item>A succinct statement of our present nuclear war doctrine. In so doing,
                            you should comment on the advisability of retaining or cancelling <gloss
                                target="#t_NSDM_1">NSDM</gloss> 242 and limited nuclear
                            options.</item>
                        <label>(b)</label>
                        <item>A brief statement of the procedures for actually conducting a nuclear
                            war, limited or total, beyond the initial phase. This should include an
                            indication of the command procedures for the conduct of such a war,
                            including such operational aspects as the location and procedures for
                            effective exercise of control. In addition, please provide your
                            assessment of the survivability of our command and control systems. The
                            Blue Ribbon Defense Panel of 1970<note n="2" xml:id="d10fn2">See <ref
                                    target="#d9fn3">footnote 3, Document 9</ref>.</note> reached
                            some disturbing conclusions regarding this matter.</item>
                        <label>(c)</label>
                        <item>A short statement of the basic objectives to be achieved through our
                            various <gloss target="#t_LNO_1">LNO</gloss> options, and some
                            indication of the assumptions, both political and military, regarding
                            the specific <gloss target="#t_LNO_1">LNO</gloss>s.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BZ_1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Zbigniew Brzezinski</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
